<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-185-314 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 541 741</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 1 1991 v8 n13 p133(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Novell resellers courted in IBM's connectivity drive.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burke, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>IBM's new connectivity strategy includes the courting of smallsystems integrators and Novell Inc's top resellers.andP;  The newstrategy to push its local area network (LAN) connectivityproducts deeper into the channel is seen by industry observers asa departure from its previously aloof attitude.andP;  IBM has alsogiven the Management Systems Group (MSG) the right to sell its LANproducts.andP;  MSG, which is the first distributor to gain the rightto sell IBM LAN products, has signed 50 independent resellers tomarket the IBM connectivity products.andP;  IBM's market share of theLAN connectivity products industry was only two percent in 1990.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Management)Novell Inc. (Products)Management Systems Group (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    IBM; NOVL.andO;Topic:     Computer systems integratorsValue-Added ResellersConnectivityLocal Area NetworksStrategic PlanningDistribution Agreements.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Management Systems Group company information. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steven BurkeandM;In an effort to push its connectivity products deeper into the channel, IBMis courting some of Novell Inc.'s top resellers as well as small systemsintegrators.andM;David Nichols, IBM's director of channel management for connectivityproducts, in Montvale, N.J., last week said IBM is interested in signingNovell's top-performing Platinum resellers as IBM resellers.andM;&quot;Until now IBM has considered the Novell Platinum resellers as second-classcitizens,&quot; said Tom Dolan, chairman of the New York Chapter of the Local AreaNetwork Dealers Association.andM;Most Platinum resellers, the most technically trained Novell dealers, havenot been authorized to sell IBM connectivity products, said Dolan.andM;IBM's change of heart comes after signing an agreement in February to sell anIBM blue box version of Novell Inc.'s NetWare network operating system.andP;  &quot;Wethink a lot of the Novell Platinum remarketers would, in our eyes, make idealcandidates for our VAR program,&quot; said Nichols.andM;The move to recruit Novell resellers isn't the only change in IBM'sdistribution strategy for connectivity products.andP;  For the first time, IBMrecently gave the green light to a distributor to sell these IBM products(see chart, above).andM;The distributor, Management Systems Group (MSG) of Hauppauge, N.Y., signed 50independent resellers to market IBM connectivity products as part of an IBMpilot program established in December.andM;The IBM products MSG is carrying include: IBM LAN OS/2 LAN Server, OS/2Extended Edition, Token-Ring adapters and 3270/5250 communications products.andM;&quot;The business we have gotten to date is almost all incremental business forIBM,&quot; said MSG President John Spielberger in Hauppauge.andM;&quot;This is business from systems integrators that were walking away fromcustomers asking for IBM solutions or recommending competitive products.&quot;andM;&quot;IBM is trying to bring more LAN expertise to its end users through systemsintegrators,&quot; said Stewart Skomra, vice president of marketing for iLAN, asystems integrator in Columbus, Ohio, that recently received permission tocarry IBM PS/2s.andP;  &quot;The retail channel has become a commodity market formoving boxes.&quot;andM;iLAN was authorized to sell PS/2s under the IBM LAN Value Added Enhancement(VAE) program.andP;  As a LAN VAE, systems integrators receive PS/2 discountpricing without being forced to meet the large volume requirements that IBMsets for its licensed dealers.andM;&quot;We are not under pressure to compromise ourselves in order to meet shipmentrequirements,&quot; Skomra said.andM;IBM's blue box version of NetWare along with increased distribution of IBM'sLAN Server may help it boost its sagging LAN network operating system marketshare, analysts said.andM;Last year, IBM's share of the network operating system market was only 2percent, compared with 53 percent for market leader Novell, according toInternational Data Corp., a Framingham, Mass., market-research firm.andO;</TEXT></DOC>